{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":51,"record_hash":"sha256:fd37666e533d4bef436fcb3be782668722074d33bf716adbe7af1b6783afb8aa","timestamp":"2026-05-07T10:51:01.072Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 223c74\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 2045\nOutput:\n# First POC Implementation Contract\n\nThis is the implementation contract for the first Agent Session Capture POC.\n\nIf this page conflicts with broader architecture or future-work notes, this page\nwins for the first implementation.\n\n## Goal\n\nBuild the smallest safe proof that GitButler can capture agent-session metadata\nfrom an explicit Codex transcript path and write it into GitMeta local storage.\n\nThe first patch should prove:\n\n- GitButler CLI can invoke capture behind a hidden feature-gated command.\n- A new crate can parse a Codex JSONL transcript from an explicit path.\n- Capture can write provenance/cursor metadata into GitMeta.\n- Optional raw transcript capture can append normalized envelope records.\n- Repeated capture is idempotent.\n\n## Implement Only This\n\n- New crate: `crates/but-capture` (`but_capture` in Rust code).\n- Hidden CLI command behind feature flag `capture`:\n\n```text\nbut agent-session capture \\\n  --agent codex \\\n  --transcript-path <path> \\\n  [--target project] \\\n  [--include-transcript] \\\n  [--dry-run]\n```\n\n- `codex` is the only supported agent in the first implementation.\n- Claude Code is the intended second agent after the Codex path works; do not\n  pre-generalize for it in the Codex patch.\n- `--transcript-path` is required.\n- Default target is `project`.\n- GitMeta writes are local only.\n- Raw transcript records are not written unless `--include-transcript` is set.\n- `--dry-run` returns the planned report and performs no GitMeta writes.\n\n## Do Not Implement Yet\n\n- No Claude Code support in the first Codex patch.\n- No Cursor support.\n- No background watcher.\n- No session discovery.\n- No `CODEX_THREAD_ID` lookup.\n- No recent-file heuristics.\n- No branch inference.\n- No commit inference from `HEAD`.\n- No GitMeta push/fetch/sync.\n- No UI surface.\n- No dependency on `but-api`, `but-db`, `but-ctx`, `but-claude`, `but-cursor`,\n  or legacy virtual branch APIs.\n\n## Dependency Decision for Lo\n[TRUNCATED]\ns a partially written record:\n  skip it and include a warning/count in the report if report supports warnings.\n- A malformed line before the final non-empty line fails the command.\n- `last-record-index` is the highest successfully parsed/captured source record\n  index; never advance it for a skipped partial final line.\n\nIf a transcript `cwd` exists, canonicalize it and accept it only when it is the\nrepo root or inside the repo worktree. Otherwise the POC should fail rather than\nguess. A future `--allow-cwd-mismatch` can relax this.\n\n## Deduplication\n\nUse stable record hashes from day one.\n\nStable record hash:\n\n```text\nsha256(trimmed raw JSONL line bytes)\n```\n\nHash before envelope wrapping. Do not include capture timestamp, source path, or\nrecord index in the hash.\n\nImportant idempotency rule: keep separate bookkeeping for records seen versus\ntranscript records appended. A metadata-only capture must not prevent a later\n`--include-transcript` run from appending transcript envelopes for the same\nsource records.\n\nFor each record:\n\n1. Trim trailing newline/whitespace from the raw JSONL line.\n2. Parse as JSON.\n3. Compute `sha256` of the trimmed raw bytes.\n4. Skip record-derived metadata for this source record if the hash already\n   exists in `seen-record-hashes`.\n5. If `--include-transcript` is set, append an envelope only if the hash is not\n   already in `transcript-record-hashes`.\n6. Store new hashes in the appropriate lists.\n\nPer-source cursor/provenance keys (`source-size`, `source-sha256`,\n`last-record-index`, `captured-at`) should still update once per successful\nnon-dry-run capture, even if all records dedupe.\n\nWhen reading `seen-record-hashes` or `transcript-record-hashes`, treat a missing\nGitMeta set key as an empty set. Read hash sets via `handle.get_value(key)?` and\ndecode `MetaValue::Set`; use `set_add()` for writes. Do not use `list_entries()`\nfor set keys. Fail only on malformed/unreadable existing set values or GitMeta\nI/O errors.\n\n## GitMeta Writes\n\nUse `git-meta-lib` public APIs where possible:\n\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-07T10:51:01.072Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}